SIMPLE: studious
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Studious
<hw>Stu"di*ous</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L.
<ets>studious</ets>: cf. F. <ets>studieux</ets>. See
<er>Study</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Given to study; devoted to the
acquisition of knowledge from books; <as>as, a <ex>studious</ex>
scholar</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Given to thought, or to the examination of subjects
by contemplation; contemplative.</def> <rj><au>Locke.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Earnest in endeavors; aiming sedulously; attentive;
observant; diligent; -- usually followed by an infinitive or by
<xex>of</xex>; <as>as, be <ex>studious</ex> to please; <ex>studious</ex>
to find new friends and allies</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>You that are so <qex>studious</qex>⟦br⟧
Of my affairs, wholly neglect your own.</q>
<rj><qau>Massinger.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>Planned with study; deliberate; studied.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>For the frigid villainy of <qex>studious</qex> lewdness, . . .
with apology can be invented?</q> <rj><qau>Rambler.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>Favorable to study; suitable for thought and
contemplation; <as>as, the <ex>studious</ex> shade</as>.</def>
<mark>[Poetic]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>But let my due feet never fail⟦br⟧
To walk the <qex>studious</qex> cloister's pale.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p>-- <wordforms><wf>Stu"di*ous*ly</wf>, <pos>adv.</pos> --
<wf>Stu"di*ous*ness</wf>, <pos>n.</pos></wordforms>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Study</ent>⟦br⟧
